OVERVIEW
This specification defines the process for generating two parallel synthetic datasets — Social Media Posts and Journalistic Articles — designed to evaluate NLP pipelines that infer geographic location from text using indirect signals rather than explicit place names.
Each dataset contains 144 entries (288 total across both datasets), evenly distributed across three signal types and six continents. The datasets are separate deliverables and are not blended or interleaved.
The three signal types test three distinct pipeline capabilities. Signal A tests entity linking: the entity name is unambiguous, but its location requires a Wikidata lookup. Signal B tests toponym disambiguation: an ambiguous place name must be resolved using contextual detail. Signal C tests entity disambiguation: an ambiguous entity name must be resolved using contextual detail, then its location looked up via Wikidata.
OUTPUT SCHEMA
Each dataset is a single CSV file with the following columns: text (the generated text), qid (Wikidata QID of the target location, e.g. Q3870), location_name (target city or town), country, continent (one of Africa, Asia, Europe, North America, South America, Oceania), signal_type (one of A, B, C), ambiguous_name (the ambiguous name used in the text — for Signal B this is the toponym, for Signal C this is the ambiguous entity name, blank for Signal A), and other_referents (semicolon-separated list of other things sharing the ambiguous name, populated for B and C, blank for A).
TEXT FORMATS
Social Media Post
Length is 1 to 3 sentences. Register should be casual, opinionated, or reactive, using natural internet language — abbreviations, slang, and sentence fragments are acceptable. Subjects include local sport, food, urban life, community events, infrastructure, culture, or current affairs. Contextual detail should feel incidental and organic, like something a real person would post, not like a deliberate geographic clue. Social media posts in English should not use non-English characters or diacritics — for example, write "Skoda" not "Škoda", "Cordoba" not "Córdoba". Journalistic articles may preserve them.
Journalistic Article
Length is 4 to 7 paragraphs, approximately 300 to 500 words. The structure must include a headline, a news lead covering who, what, and when, at least one attributed quote from a role-based source (for example "a club spokesperson said", "one local vendor explained", "according to a council official" — do not use named individuals in quotes as real names may create unintended entity-linking signals that interfere with signal type purity), at least one reference to a named organisation, and a forward-looking closing sentence. Subjects include local sport, business, urban development, infrastructure, culture, food, or community affairs. Contextual detail should feel like natural journalistic background, not a deliberate geographic clue.
Physical Presence Rule
This applies to all formats and all signal types. The person or narrative voice in the text must be physically present in the target location. Events watched on screens, read about online, or experienced remotely do not provide valid location signals. The contextual detail that disambiguates the location must come from the person's direct physical environment — what they see, hear, walk through, commute past, eat, and experience with their body.

SIGNAL TYPES

Each dataset contains 48 entries per signal type (A, B, and C).
4.1 Signal A — Entity Linking (Unambiguous Entity)
The core requirement is that the text contains at least one named entity formally associated with the target location and verifiable via Wikidata. The entity name must be unambiguous. There must be no explicit geographic information. What this tests: the entity name is clear — a reader can identify which entity is being referenced — but they cannot know where it is located without consulting Wikidata.
At least one Wikidata-verifiable entity must appear per text. Entities must be real people, organisations, or events whose Wikidata entries formally link them to the target location. No other entity types such as creative works, products, or concepts are permitted as primary signals.
Entity names must be unambiguous — they must clearly resolve to a single Wikidata item. A reader should be able to identify which entity is being referenced without confusion. Entity names shared by multiple well-known entities (such as "Sparta", "Racing", "United", "Victoria") must not be used in Signal A and belong in Signal C instead.
Entities must be city-specific, not country-level. National brands, national celebrities, and nationally-distributed products are not valid Signal A entities even if their Wikidata headquarters property points to the target city. The entity should be something a person encounters because they live in that specific city — a local football club, a local politician, a regional business, a city-specific event. If the entity operates nationwide and is equally associated with the whole country, it is too broad.
Entities whose official name contains the target location name are forbidden — for example, "Talleres de Córdoba" cannot be used for Córdoba and "Alianza Lima" cannot be used for Lima. Entities widely understood as synonymous with or metonymic for the location are forbidden, such as Hollywood for Los Angeles or Wall Street for New York. Entities named after famous local landmarks are also forbidden.
If a general-knowledge reader who does not use Wikidata could identify the location from the entity name alone, the entity is too obvious. As a soft heuristic: if the entity's English Wikipedia article mentions the target city in the opening sentence and the entity is widely known internationally, consider it too iconic.
The entity's Wikidata item must contain a property that formally links it to the target location. Acceptable properties include P19 (place of birth), P159 (headquarters location), P131 (located in the administrative territorial entity), P5 4 (member of sports team, where the team is linked to the location), and P937 (work location). Chains through P17 then P131 are acceptable (for example, person born in suburb, suburb is part of target city), but the chain must not exceed two hops.
The following geographic content is absolutely forbidden in Signal A: city, town, and village names; country, state, province, and region names; street, road, and neighbourhood names; landmark names including bridges, mountains, rivers, parks, and famous buildings; nationality adjectives and demonyms such as "French", "Kenyan", or "Carioca"; directional descriptors that identify a region such as "the South" or "East Coast"; and named transport systems identifiable to a single city such as "Gautrain" or "the Tube".
After writing the text, perform a self-check by reading back every word and asking: could this word appear on a map, in a geography textbook, or in a country-specific glossary? If yes, remove or replace it.
Natural, incidental detail about everyday life, local culture, sport, weather, food, or current affairs is permitted as background texture — see Section 6 for the grey-area rules on culturally locating language. Contextual detail should reinforce city-level location where possible through local terrain, local weather patterns distinct within the country, urban character, local food specialties, and local transport quirks, all without naming anything. The goal is that the entity provides the Wikidata-linkable signal and the context makes it feel grounded in a specific place rather than a generic national setting.
4.2 Signal B — Toponym Disambiguation (Ambiguous Place Name)
The core requirement is that the text contains an ambiguous toponym (place name) that refers to the target location but could plausibly refer to other places, people, brands, or concepts. What this tests: the place name is ambiguous — a reader cannot know which location is meant without contextual detail. The pipeline must use surrounding context to disambiguate.
The toponym must appear naturally within the text and must not feel forced or artificial. It must be genuinely ambiguous to a reader without regional familiarity — it should be plausible that it refers to at least 3 other referents as described in the toponym selection criteria in Section 5.2. The text must contain enough natural contextual detail about local life, culture, sport, weather, infrastructure, or current affairs that a reader with regional familiarity could reasonably infer which location is meant. A reader without regional familiarity should find the toponym genuinely ambiguous — the disambiguation should require local knowledge, not general English proficiency.
The following are forbidden in Signal B: named entities linkable via Wikidata as a primary signal (incidental mentions of real people or organisations are acceptable only if they do not themselves reveal the location), nationality adjectives or demonyms, metonymy, and any explicit geographic information beyond the toponym itself and natural contextual detail.
4.3 Signal C — Entity Disambiguation (Ambiguous Entity Name)
The core requirement is that the text contains at least one named entity (person, organisation, or event) whose name is shared by multiple well-known entities. The entity name must be genuinely ambiguous — a reader encountering the name without context could reasonably think it refers to a different entity. The text must contain enough natural contextual detail that a reader familiar with the target location could infer which entity is meant, and therefore which location.
What this tests: the entity name is ambiguous — "Sparta", "Racing", "United", "Sporting" and so on. The pipeline must first figure out which entity using contextual detail, then look up that entity's location via Wikidata. This is a distinct skill from Signal A (where the entity is clear) and Signal B (where a place name is ambiguous).
The entity name as written in the text must have at least 3 documented alternative referents (other entities sharing the same name) listed in the other_referents field. The entity must be verifiable via Wikidata and formally linked to the target location. The entity must not be the most famous bearer of the name — if a reader sees the name with no context and defaults to one specific entity, that entity is a poor choice (for example, "Arsenal" overwhelmingly suggests London). The entity's full disambiguated name must not appear in the text — write "Sporting" not "Sporting Lisbon", write "Racing" not "Racing Club de Avellaneda".
The text must contain enough natural detail about local life, terrain, weather, culture, or urban character that a reader with regional familiarity can infer which entity is meant. A reader without regional familiarity should find the entity name genuinely ambiguous. Contextual detail should reinforce city-level location, not just country-level.
The following are forbidden in Signal C: explicit geographic information including city, country, and region names, nationality adjectives, and demonyms; the entity's full disambiguated name; and any direct statement of which entity is meant.
The Wikidata linkage requirement is the same as Signal A — the entity's Wikidata item must contain a property formally linking it to the target location.

LOCATION AND ENTITY SELECTION

5.1 Location Selection Criteria
All target locations must be real cities or towns with a Wikidata entry. No city may appear more than once within the same signal type in a single dataset. A city may appear across different signal types (for example once in Signal A and once in Signal B) but this should be minimised. No country may contribute more than 2 locations per continent per signal type to ensure within-continent diversity. There is no minimum population threshold, but the location must have enough associated Wikidata entities (for Signal A and C) or a suitably ambiguous name (for Signal B) to support generation. Favour lesser-known cities over capital cities and globally famous metropolises, especially for underrepresented continents.
5.2 Toponym Selection Criteria (Signal B)
The toponym is the name, or part of the name, of the target location that is ambiguous. It must have at least 3 documented alternative referents — other places, people, brands, or concepts sharing the same name. Alternative referents should be sourced from Wikidata disambiguation pages or Wikipedia disambiguation pages for the toponym. Manual identification is acceptable if documented. Referents may include other cities or towns with the same name (ideally on different continents), surnames, given names, brand names, fictional characters, films, songs, or other cultural products. The other_referents field must list these as a semicolon-separated string.
Quality test: if a reader sees the toponym with no other context, they should not default to the target location. If the target location is the most famous bearer of the name (for example "Paris" overwhelmingly suggests France), it is a poor toponym choice unless the text provides strong misdirection or the alternative referents are also well-known.
5.3 Ambiguous Entity Selection Criteria (Signal C)
The ambiguous entity is a person, organisation, or event whose name is shared by multiple well-known entities. The entity name must have at least 3 documented alternative referents — other entities (not places) sharing the same name. Alternative referents should be sourced from Wikidata disambiguation pages or Wikipedia. Manual identification is acceptable if documented. Referents may include other sports clubs, other organisations, other people, brands, or cultural concepts sharing the name. The entity must not be the most famous bearer of the name. The entity's Wikidata item must formally link to the target location.
Quality test: if a reader sees the entity name with no context, they should not default to the target entity. Multiple plausible interpretations should exist.
5.4 Location Selection Process
First, for each continent, compile a candidate list of 15 to 20 cities or towns that meet the criteria above. Second, for Signal A, verify that at least one unambiguous, city-specific Wikidata entity exists for each candidate city and discard candidates where this fails. Third, for Signal B, verify that the city name or a component of it is genuinely ambiguous with at least 3 alternative referents and discard candidates where this fails. Fourth, for Signal C, verify that the city has at least one entity with an ambiguous name (3 or more alternative referents) that is linked to the city via Wikidata and discard candidates where this fails. Fifth, select 8 cities per continent per signal type from the verified candidates. Sixth, document the selected cities and their associated entities, toponyms, and ambiguous entities before generating text.

GREY AREAS — CULTURALLY LOCATING LANGUAGE

Different signal types have different tolerances for culturally specific language.
6.1 Signal A (strictest)
Signal A forbids all explicit geographic information. Currency references such as "rand" or "peso" are not permitted because currencies map directly to countries. Language-specific loanwords used in English such as "braai" or "feria" are permitted with caution — they are allowed if the word has entered casual English usage in the relevant region, but if the word is essentially a unique identifier for one country or culture, use it sparingly. Food references such as "empanadas" or "pho" are permitted with caution as background texture, but avoid foods that uniquely identify a single city and prefer foods associated with a broad region or multiple countries. Climate and weather descriptions are permitted — "it was 40 degrees and humid" is fine because these narrow the geography without naming it. Unnamed sport references are permitted — referring to "the league" or "the derby" without naming it is fine. Slang and dialect markers are permitted and encouraged for texture.
6.2 Signal B and C (more permissive)
All of the above are permitted more freely, as Signals B and C rely on contextual detail for disambiguation. The only prohibitions remain: no explicit place names (other than the toponym in Signal B), no nationality adjectives, no demonyms, and no metonymy. For Signal C, the entity's full disambiguated name is also forbidden.

CONTINENT DISTRIBUTION

Each signal type contains 48 entries, distributed as 8 entries per continent across Africa, Asia, Europe, North America, South America, and Oceania. This applies identically to both the Social Media and Journalistic Article datasets.
Total per dataset: 144 entries (48 times 3 signal types). Grand total: 288 entries (144 times 2 datasets).

QUALITY CONTROL CHECKLIST
Every generated entry must pass the following checks before inclusion.
8.1 All Signal Types
The text reads naturally and sounds like something a real person or journalist would write. The target location is never named directly in the text. No country names appear in the text. No nationality adjectives or demonyms appear in the text. No region, state, or province names appear in the text. The qid is a valid Wikidata identifier for the target city or town. The location_name, country, and continent are consistent with the qid. The text is in English. The person or narrative voice is physically present in the target location and not watching remotely.
8.2 Signal A Specific
At least one named entity is present in the text. Each entity has a Wikidata item with a property formally linking it to the target location with a maximum 2-hop chain. No entity's official name contains the target location name. No entity name is ambiguous, meaning it is not shared by multiple well-known entities. The entity is city-specific and not a national brand or celebrity equally associated with the whole country. No entity is so culturally iconic that a general-knowledge reader would immediately identify the location. The full self-check has been completed and no word in the text could appear on a map or in a geography textbook. There are no currency references. There are no named transport systems, landmarks, or streets. Contextual detail reinforces city-level, not just country-level, setting.
8.3 Signal B Specific
The toponym appears in the text. The toponym has at least 3 documented alternative referents listed in other_referents. A reader with regional familiarity could reasonably infer the correct location. A reader without regional familiarity would find the toponym genuinely ambiguous. No Wikidata-linkable entities serve as a primary location signal.
8.4 Signal C Specific
The ambiguous entity name appears in the text. The entity name has at least 3 documented alternative referents listed in other_referents. The entity's full disambiguated name does not appear in the text. The entity's Wikidata item formally links to the target location. A reader with regional familiarity could reasonably infer which entity is meant. A reader without regional familiarity would find the entity name genuinely ambiguous. No explicit geographic information appears in the text. Contextual detail reinforces city-level, not just country-level, setting.

REPRODUCIBILITY NOTES

9.1 Generation Metadata
Each generation run should document the model used (for example Claude Opus 4.6), the date of generation in ISO format, the date of Wikidata verification (since QIDs and entity-location links should be verified on or near the generation date as they can change over time), and the spec version referenced.
9.2 Process
First, select locations per Section 5.4. Second, for each location, identify entities for Signal A, toponym plus referents for Signal B, or ambiguous entity plus referents for Signal C. Third, generate text per the format and signal type rules. Fourth, run the quality control checklist from Section 8 on every entry. Fifth, fix or discard entries that fail any check. Sixth, compile into two CSV files, one for Social Media and one for Journalistic Articles.
9.3 Known Limitations
The cultural familiarity test for entity iconicity in Section 4.1 is inherently subjective and different generators may draw the line differently. The disambiguation difficulty of Signal B and C entries is calibrated to regional familiarity which is not a quantifiable threshold, so empirical evaluation with human annotators is recommended after generation. Wikidata coverage is uneven across continents and some locations in Africa, South America, and Oceania may have fewer verifiable entities, making Signal A and C generation harder — if a location cannot support a valid entity after reasonable search, replace it with another candidate from the same continent. Signal C requires entities with ambiguous names that are also linked to specific cities via Wikidata, which is a narrow requirement and may limit location diversity for Signal C compared to Signals A and B.
